answers.body_markdown:
&gt; Earlier I was trying /@(\w+)/g but it trims out -wiy from the word
&gt; yoker

Because \w includes `alphabets ( both case ), digits and _` not `-` so you get only utpo `@yorker`

---

Simply you can use `split`, `filter` and  `startsWith`

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    let str = &#39;@yoMan is going crazy with @yoker-wiy&#39;;
    let final = str.split(/\s+/)
                   .filter(v =&gt; v.startsWith(&#39;@&#39;))
    console.log(final)

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


---

With match you can use  `@[^\s]+`

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    let str = &#39;@yoMan is going crazy with @yoker-wiy&#39;;
    let final = str.match(/@[^\s]+/g)
                 
    console.log(final)

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const re = &#39;@yoMan is going crazy with @yoker-wiy&#39;.match(/(?:^|\W)@(\w+|^-)(?!\w)/g);
       console.log(re);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

This is the regex that you are looking for.

You need to change the word-boundaries (`\b`) to a line-start (`^`) and line-end (`$`) and it will work.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    console.log(
      &#39;@yoMan is going crazy with @yoker-wiy&#39;
        .split(/\s+/g)
        .filter(s =&gt; s.match(/^@\S+$/g))
    );

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .as-console-wrapper { top: 0; max-height: 100% !important; }

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

